{"title_page": "Waheed Alli, Baron Alli", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n|name = The Lord Alli\n|honorific-suffix =\n|image = Waheed Alli 2010.jpg\n|imagesize =\n|smallimage =\n|caption =\n|office          = [[Chancellor (education)|Chancellor]] of [[De Montfort University]]\n|1blankname      = [[Chancellor (education)#Vice-chancellor|Vice-Chancellor]]\n|1namedata       = Philip Tasker<br/>[[Dominic Shellard]]\n|term_start      = 2006\n|term_end        = 2015\n|predecessor      = [[Usha Prashar, Baroness Prashar|The Baroness Prashar]]\n|successor        = [[Doreen Lawrence|The Baroness Lawrence]]\n|office2         = [[Members of the House of Lords|Member]] of the [[House of Lords]]<br/><small>[[Lords Temporal|Lord Temporal]]</small>\n|term_start2       = 18 July 1998<br/><small>[[Life peer|Life Peerage]]</small>\n|term_end2       =\n|birthname = Waheed Alli\n|birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1964|11|16}}\n|birth_place = [[Croydon]], London, UK\n|death_date =\n|death_place =\n|nationality = British\n|restingplace =\n|restingplacecoordinates =\n|partner =\n|profession = Media entrepreneur\n\n|party = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]\n}}\n'''Waheed Alli, Baron Alli''' (born 16 November 1964) is a media entrepreneur and politician. He is the co-creator of the television series ''[[Survivor (franchise)|Survivor]]'' and has held executive positions at several television production companies including the [[Endemol Shine Group]], Carlton Television Productions (now [[ITV Studios]]), [[Planet 24]], and [[Chorion (company)|Chorion]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/markets/stocks|title=Executive Profile: Waheed Alli|last=|first=|date=|website=Bloomberg.com|access-date=2018-02-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/f43ebf70-ef34-11e0-918b-00144feab49a|title=Lunch with the FT: Waheed Alli|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nHe is currently the Chief Executive of [[Silvergate Media]], Chairman of Koovs Plc and a director at [[Olga TV|Olga Productions]]. He is a member of the [[House of Lords]] in the United Kingdom, sitting as a [[life peer]] for the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]], and is described as one of only a few openly [[Islam and sexual orientation|gay Muslim]] politicians in the world.<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/religion/7386492/Lord-Alli-attacks-bishops-in-gay-marriage-row.html|title=Lord Alli attacks bishops in 'gay marriage' row|last=Alderson|first=Andrew|newspaper=Telegraph|quote= one of the few openly-gay Muslim politicians |accessdate=25 April 2012|date=6 March 2010}}     \n</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/2/f43ebf70-ef34-11e0-918b-00144feab49a.html|title=Lunch with the FT: Waheed Alli|last=Edgecliffe-Johnson|first=Andrew|publisher=FT|quote=one of the few gay Muslims in British public life.|accessdate=28 February 2012}}</ref>\n\nWaheed is also well known \n\n<br />\n\n==Biography==\nIn British political terms he is considered [[British Asian|Asian]], because both of his parents are [[Indo-Caribbean]]. His mother, a nurse, is an [[Indo-Trinidadian]] from [[Trinidad and Tobago]], and his estranged father, a mechanic, is an [[Indo-Guyanese]] from [[Guyana]]. His mother was [[Hindu]] and his father [[Muslim]]; he has two brothers, who are also Muslims.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2002/jun/17/religion.immigrationpolicy|title=Profiles of 10 leading British Muslims|author1=Vasagar, Jeevan |author2=Kelso, Paul |author3=James-Gregory, Sally |author4=Dodd, Vikram |date=17 June 2002|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=26 April 2012|location=London}}</ref> He was named one of the 20 most important Asians in British media in 2005.<ref name=\"AIM\">[http://www.asiansinmedia.org/top20/2005/1.php Most Powerful Asians in British Media: Lord Waheed Alli]. ''Asians in Media''</ref> At the same time, he maintains ties with his Caribbean roots, both with other British-Guyanese politicians such as [[Valerie Amos]] and [[Trevor Phillips]], and with President [[Bharrat Jagdeo]].<ref name=\"CV\">John Muir, [http://www.caribvoice.org/Profiles/peers.html \"Caribbean Peers\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927202004/http://www.caribvoice.org/Profiles/peers.html |date=27 September 2007 }}, Caribbean Voice, October 2001.</ref>\n\nHe is one of a group of highly successful Guyanese people in Britain ([[Michael White (journalist)|Michael White]] of ''[[The Guardian]]'' refers to them as the \"Guyanese mafia\"), which includes [[Raj Persaud]], [[Herman Ouseley]]<ref>Michael White, [https://www.theguardian.com/politics/blog/2009/aug/27/balls-gcse-results-michael-white \"Balls gets his retaliation in first as annual GCSE row begins\"], ''The Guardian'', 27 August 2009.</ref> and [[David Dabydeen]], [[Cynthia Pine]], [[Keith Waithe]] and [[Rudolph Dunbar]].<ref>''Guyanese Achievers UK'' (2007) by Dindayal Vidur.</ref>\n\nAlli grew up in humble surroundings, attended [[Harris Academy South Norwood|Stanley Technical College]] in [[South Norwood]] and left school at 16 with nine [[O-levels]].<ref name=\"KC\">[http://www.knittingcircle.org.uk/waheedalli.html Knitting Circle.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070307031738/http://www.knittingcircle.org.uk/waheedalli.html |date=7 March 2007 }}</ref>\n\n==Business career==\nAlli started work as a junior researcher for a finance magazine, crediting his first success to Salem Ghayar, who hired and mentored him.  After a few years of preparing monthly reports for potential investors, he was headhunted by Save & Prosper, part of [[Robert Fleming & Co.]].<ref name=\"asianoutlook.com\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20030308075823/http://www.asianoutlook.com/lordali.htm Interviewed by Shahid]. ''The Asian Outlook''. No date; approximately 2001.</ref> Eventually he returned to his original employer, and worked his way up in the media business within [[Robert Maxwell]]'s stable of publications.  He then went to [[City of London|the City]] for a second career in [[investment banking]], through which he became wealthy.<ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/1047062.stm|title=Profile: Lord Waheed Alli|date=29 November 2000|work=[[BBC News Online]]|accessdate=24 May 2009}}</ref> In the mid-1980s he met [[Charlie Parsons]], who was to become his business partner as well as his life partner.<ref name=\"The Independent (Saturday 06 June 2015)\">{{cite web|title=The Party Boys|publisher=The Independent. Saturday, 6 June 2015|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/the-party-boys-1196428.html|website=}}</ref>\n\nAlli's third career, and the first in which he achieved public prominence, was in the television industry.  He and Parsons set up [[24 Hour Productions]], which produced ''[[The Word (TV series)|The Word]]'', \"the most talked about television programme in Britain\".<ref name=\"KC\" /> In 1992 they merged with [[Bob Geldof]]'s [[Planet Pictures]] to form [[Planet 24]].  Such was its success that it became one of the largest TV production companies in the country, and the main independent supplier to [[Channel 4]].<ref name=\"KC\" /> It was responsible for genre-breaking programmes such as ''Big Breakfast'' and ''[[Survivor (TV series)|Survivor]]''. [[Carlton Television]] bought Planet 24 in March 1999 for \u00a315 million, with Alli and Parsons prudently retaining the rights to the lucrative ''Survivor'' format. Waheed Alli became a Carlton board director before stepping down a year later.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2002/jun/17/religion.immigrationpolicy|title=Profiles of 10 leading British Muslims|author1=Vasagar, Jeevan |author2=Kelso, Paul |author3=James-Gregory, Sally |author4=Dodd, Vikram |date=17 June 2002|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=24 May 2009|location=London}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2003 Alli took over as chairman of the [[intellectual property|media rights]] company [[Chorion (company)|Chorion Ltd]],<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/2871751/Hands-off-Noddy.html | location=London | work=The Daily Telegraph | title=Hands off Noddy! | date=14 December 2003}}</ref> which owns rights to [[Enid Blyton]] and [[Agatha Christie]], and has offices beyond the UK in New York, Sydney, and Tokyo.<ref name=\"AIM\" /> He was chairman of [[Alternative Investment Market|AIM]]-listed [[ASOS.com]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/business/8124164.stm|title=Overseas sales boost Asos profits|date=29 June 2009|work=[[bbc.co.uk]]|accessdate=29 June 2009}}</ref> and a director of [[Olga Television]], entertainer [[Paul O'Grady]]'s [[production company]]. He owns part of [[Shine Limited]], a media production company he co-founded in March 2001 with [[Elisabeth Murdoch (businesswoman)|Elisabeth Murdoch]], daughter of media-magnate [[Rupert Murdoch]]. In August 2011, he stepped down from the chairmanship of Chorion and sold half his stake in ASOS.com to start a new company called Silvergate Media.{{Citation needed|date=September 2012|reason=please provide source or remove}}\n\nHe was part of a failed \u00a3100m bid backed by [[private equity]] firm [[3i]] to buy [[Virgin Radio]] from [[SMG plc]] in 2005. In March 2007 he was appointed as SMG's non-executive director.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2007/mar/05/smg.citynews|title=SMG makes board appointments|last=Holmwood|first=Leigh|date=5 March 2007|work=[[guardian.co.uk]]|accessdate=24 May 2009|location=London}}</ref>\n\nAlli is a founder investor in Koovs, an Indian online retailer looking to replicate the success of Asos in the subcontinent. The company was set up in 2012 and intends to raise \u00a322m with a stock market listing on London's Aim.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/b8586954-4bb5-11e3-a02f-00144feabdc0.html#axzz2kVSow9B5|author=Duncan Robinson|work=Financial Times|date=12 November 2013|title=Ex-Asos boss to list Indian venture on Aim}}</ref>\nIn December 2019 the company goes into administration after funding isn't found.  The company is bought by SGIK 3 for 250,000. Shareholders lose millions.  SGIK 3 is Lord Ali's company, set up in the weeks prior to the collapse.<ref>https://www.morningstar.co.uk/uk/news/AN_1576002908644184200/update-koovs-sold-to-sgik-3-after-falling-in-administration.aspx</ref>\n==Politics==\nAlli joined the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] at the persuasion of his neighbour [[Emily Thornberry]], to whom he remains close.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2009/may/19/emily-thornberry-islington-mps-expenses |work=[[The Guardian]] |first=Aida |last=Edemariam |title=Right, so just what do you do all day? |date=19 May 2009 }}</ref> He is also close to [[Anji Hunter]], Director of Government Relations in [[Tony Blair]]'s first government.<ref>{{Cite news |first=Kamal |last=Ahmed |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2002/jun/02/tonyblair.schools |title=Inside Labour's young boy (and girl) network |work=[[The Observer]] |date=2 June 2002 }}</ref> [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|Prime Minister]] Blair used him for years as a means to help him reach out to a younger generation (aka \"[[Youth subculture|yoof culture]]\"),<ref name=\"BBC\" /> and as such he is considered{{by whom|date=July 2013}} one of \"[[Tony's Cronies]]\".<ref name=\"CV\" /> He was made a [[life peer]] as '''Baron Alli''', of [[Norbury]] in the [[London Borough of Croydon]], on 18 July 1998<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=55203 |date=22 July 1998 |page=7983}}</ref><ref>[https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/ld199798/minutes/980721/ldminute.htm Minutes and Order Paper \u2013 Minutes of Proceedings \u2013 The House of Lords] Parliament (19 July 1998). Retrieved on 15 March 2013.</ref> at the age of 34, becoming the youngest and the first openly gay peer in [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|Parliament]]. He sits on the Labour benches in the [[House of Lords]]. The [[BBC]] summarised his appointment as \"the antithesis of the stereotypical '[[The Establishment|establishment]]' peer \u2013 young, Asian and from the world of media and entertainment\".<ref name=\"BBC\"/>\n\nAlli has used his political position to argue for [[gay rights]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://kooth.com/|title=Kooth {{!}} Home|website=kooth.com|language=en|access-date=2018-04-23}}</ref> He spearheaded the campaign to repeal [[Section 28]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.gmax.co.za/think/history/2006/060316-clause28.html |title=What was Clause 28? |first=Liz |last=Highleyman |work=Gmax |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060814052339/http://www.gmax.co.za/think/history/2006/060316-clause28.html |date=16 February 2006 |archivedate=14 August 2006 |accessdate=24 June 2017 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> He advocated lowering the [[age of consent]] for homosexuals from 18 to 16, equal to heterosexuals; this eventually became law as the [[Sexual Offences (Amendment) Act 2000]]. It was during a heated exchange with conservative opponents, led by [[Janet Young, Baroness Young|Baroness Young]], that he informed his fellow peers that he was gay. In April 1999, he said in a speech, \"I have never been confused about my sexuality. I have been confused about the way I am treated as a result of it. The only confusion lies in the prejudice shown, some of it tonight [i.e. in the House], and much of it enshrined in the law.\"<ref name=\"BBC\"/><ref name=\"Hansard: Sexual Offences (Amendment) Act 2000\">{{cite Hansard |jurisdiction=United Kingdom |title=HL Deb 13 April 1999 vol 599 c737 |url=http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/lords/1999/apr/13/sexual-offences-amendment-bill#S5LV0599P0_19990413_HOL_256 |house=[[House of Lords]] |date=13 April 1999 |column=737 |speaker=Waheed Alli, Baron Alli |position=}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006, he participated the [[2006 World Outgames#International Conference on LGBT Human Rights|International Conference on LGBT Human Rights]] adopting [[Declaration of Montreal]] and in 2009, he spearheaded an effort to repeal clauses in the [[Civil Partnership Act 2004]] which prohibited religious institutions from conducting the ceremonies on their premises.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.churchofengland.org/our-views/home-and-community-affairs/home-affairs-policy/equality-bill/lord-alli's-amendment.aspx |title=Lord Alli's amendment |publisher=[[Church of England]] }}{{dead link |date=June 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/religion/7386492/Lord-Alli-attacks-bishops-in-gay-marriage-row.html |title=Lord Alli attacks bishops in 'gay marriage' row |last=Alderson |first=Andrew |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |quote=one of the few openly-gay Muslim politicians |accessdate=25 April 2012 |date=6 March 2010 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/8546827.stm |title=Church gay ceremonies ban lifted |work=[[BBC News Online]] |date=3 March 2010 }}</ref> This campaign culminated in a bipartisan amendment, which became part of the [[Equality Act 2010]].<ref>{{Cite news |first=Jerome |last=Taylor |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/gay-weddings-to-be-allowed-in-church-1915467.html |title=Gay weddings to be allowed in church |work=[[The Independent]] |date=3 March 2010 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-16203951 |title=Peer drops fight over same-sex ceremonies in churches |work=[[BBC News Online]] |date=15 December 2011 }}</ref> He influenced the draft Communications Bill in 2003.<ref name=\"AIM\" />\n\n==Other activities==\nAlli's work has been focused around gay rights, youth and education.  He is the former [[Chancellor (education)|Chancellor]] of [[De Montfort University]] in [[Leicester]]. He is also the President of the [[Croydon]] Youth Development Trust.<ref>[http://www.cydt.org.uk/index.html Croydon Youth Development Trust] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060620100247/http://www.cydt.org.uk/index.html |date=20 June 2006 }}</ref> He is a patron of Skillset,<ref>[http://www.skillset.org/skillset/governance/article_1844_1.asp Skillset Board of Patrons] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101129220527/http://skillset.org/skillset/governance/article_1844_1.asp |date=29 November 2010 }}</ref> the [[Sector Skills Council]] supporting skills and training within the creative media industries.\n\nIn Autumn 2008 he won a [[Stonewall Awards|Stonewall Award]] for the category of political figure. In 2002 he became a patron of [[The Albert Kennedy Trust]], stating: \"Being a teenager isn't easy and it's particularly difficult for vulnerable and [[social exclusion|socially excluded]] members of our community. The Albert Kennedy Trust offers young [[LGBT|gay men, lesbians and bisexuals]] a unique and targeted service. My first task as Patron will be to support plans to extend these services across the UK, to help the increasing number of young people contacting the Trust.\" He was a [[keynote speaker]] at the International Conference on [[LGBT social movements|LGBT Human Rights]], part of the [[2006 World Outgames]], which led to the [[Declaration of Montreal]]. Alli is a patron of Oxford Pride, the annual [[Pride parade|Pride event]] in Oxfordshire, and of [[Pride London]]. He is a patron of the [[Elton John AIDS Foundation]].<ref>[http://ejaf.com/about/our-patrons/ Elton John AIDS Foundation patrons]</ref>\n\nA portrait of Alli is in the [[National Portrait Gallery (United Kingdom)|National Portrait Gallery]] collection,<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20040926215213/http://www.npg.org.uk/live/search/person.asp?LinkID=mp66357 \"Waheed Alli, Baron Alli (1964-), Television producer and politician\"], National Portrait Gallery.</ref> which contains \"portraits of the Nation's great men and women\".<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.npg.org.uk/collections/about/primary-collection/learn-more-primary.php | title = National Portrait Gallery \u2013 Introduction to the Primary Collection | accessdate = 18 June 2013 | quote = \" The collections fulfil two enduring functions: to display portraits of the Nation's great men and women [and] to act as a national focus for the study and understanding of portraits and portraiture.\"}}</ref>\n\n==Arms==\n{{Infobox COA wide\n|image = [[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|centre|150px]][[File:Alli Escutcheon.png|centre|200px]]\n|escutcheon = Azure on a Cross Argent between four Suns issuing from the dexter and sinister chief and from the dexter and sinister base a Cross flory Gules each limb banded Or\n|crest = A Scarlet Ibis proper grasping in the sinister claws a Rose Gules barbed seeded slipped and leaved Or\n|supporters = On either side a Jaguar Or spotted Azure grasping in the interior forefoot a Sugar Cain Or\n|motto = Pro multis non pro paucis <ref>http://www.cracroftspeerage.co.uk/online/content/lp1958%20a.htm</ref>\n|badge = Out of a Rim Or fimbriated Argent the Jaguar Heads conjoined Or spotted Azure }}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|United Kingdom|Biography|Politics|LGBT}}\n*{{UK Peer links |parliament = waheed-alli/26958 |hansard = mr-waheed-alli |hansardcurr= 3639 |guardian= |publicwhip = Lord_Alli |theywork= lord_alli | record = Waheed-Alli/1834 | bbc = 26958.stm | journalisted = waheed-alli }}\n*[https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/ld199798/minutes/980721/ldminute.htm Announcement of his introduction at the House of Lords], House of Lords minutes of proceedings, 21 July 1998\n*[http://oxfordpride.org.uk Oxford Pride]\n*[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/1047062.stm  BBC profile], 29 November 2000.\n*[http://www.asiansinmedia.org/top20/2005/1.php Asians in Media profile], 2005.\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070927202004/http://www.caribvoice.org/Profiles/peers.html Caribbean Voice profile], October 2001.\n*[http://www.knittingcircle.org.uk/waheedalli Knitting Circle profile]{{dead link|date=May 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, with press cuttings\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070403225421/http://www.akt.org.uk/patrons.htm The Albert Kennedy Trust]\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-aca}}\n{{Succession box\n  | title  = [[De Montfort University|Chancellor of De Montfort University]]\n  | years  = 2006\u20132015\n  | before = [[Usha Prashar, Baroness Prashar|Baroness Usha Prashar]]\n  | after = [[Doreen Lawrence|Baroness Doreen Lawrence]]\n}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Alli, Waheed Alli, Baron}}\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:British politicians of Indian descent]]\n[[Category:Gay politicians]]\n[[Category:LGBT Muslims]]\n[[Category:English businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) life peers]]\n[[Category:English people of Indo-Guyanese descent]]\n[[Category:English people of Indo-Trinidadian descent]]\n[[Category:English Muslims]]\n[[Category:People associated with De Montfort University]]\n[[Category:LGBT businesspeople from the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:LGBT politicians from England]]\n[[Category:LGBT life peers]]\n[[Category:Gay peers]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n|name = The Lord Alli\n|honorific-suffix =\n|image = Waheed Alli 2010.jpg\n|imagesize =\n|smallimage =\n|caption =\n|office          = [[Chancellor (education)|Chancellor]] of [[De Montfort University]]\n|1blankname      = [[Chancellor (education)#Vice-chancellor|Vice-Chancellor]]\n|1namedata       = Philip Tasker<br/>[[Dominic Shellard]]\n|term_start      = 2006\n|term_end        = 2015\n|predecessor      = [[Usha Prashar, Baroness Prashar|The Baroness Prashar]]\n|successor        = [[Doreen Lawrence|The Baroness Lawrence]]\n|office2         = [[Members of the House of Lords|Member]] of the [[House of Lords]]<br/><small>[[Lords Temporal|Lord Temporal]]</small>\n|term_start2       = 18 July 1998<br/><small>[[Life peer|Life Peerage]]</small>\n|term_end2       =\n|birthname = Waheed Alli\n|birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1964|11|16}}\n|birth_place = [[Croydon]], London, UK\n|death_date =\n|death_place =\n|nationality = British\n|restingplace =\n|restingplacecoordinates =\n|partner =\n|profession = Media entrepreneur\n\n|party = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]\n}}\n'''Waheed Alli, Baron Alli''' (born 16 November 1964) is a media entrepreneur and politician. He is the co-creator of the television series ''[[Survivor (franchise)|Survivor]]'' and has held executive positions at several television production companies including the [[Endemol Shine Group]], Carlton Television Productions (now [[ITV Studios]]), [[Planet 24]], and [[Chorion (company)|Chorion]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/markets/stocks|title=Executive Profile: Waheed Alli|last=|first=|date=|website=Bloomberg.com|access-date=2018-02-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/f43ebf70-ef34-11e0-918b-00144feab49a|title=Lunch with the FT: Waheed Alli|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nHe is currently the Chief Executive of [[Silvergate Media]], Chairman of Koovs Plc and a director at [[Olga TV|Olga Productions]]. He is a member of the [[House of Lords]] in the United Kingdom, sitting as a [[life peer]] for the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]], and is described as one of only a few openly [[Islam and sexual orientation|gay Muslim]] politicians in the world.<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/religion/7386492/Lord-Alli-attacks-bishops-in-gay-marriage-row.html|title=Lord Alli attacks bishops in 'gay marriage' row|last=Alderson|first=Andrew|newspaper=Telegraph|quote= one of the few openly-gay Muslim politicians |accessdate=25 April 2012|date=6 March 2010}}     \n</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/2/f43ebf70-ef34-11e0-918b-00144feab49a.html|title=Lunch with the FT: Waheed Alli|last=Edgecliffe-Johnson|first=Andrew|publisher=FT|quote=one of the few gay Muslims in British public life.|accessdate=28 February 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nIn British political terms he is considered [[British Asian|Asian]], because both of his parents are [[Indo-Caribbean]]. His mother, a nurse, is an [[Indo-Trinidadian]] from [[Trinidad and Tobago]], and his estranged father, a mechanic, is an [[Indo-Guyanese]] from [[Guyana]]. His mother was [[Hindu]] and his father [[Muslim]]; he has two brothers, who are also Muslims.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2002/jun/17/religion.immigrationpolicy|title=Profiles of 10 leading British Muslims|author1=Vasagar, Jeevan |author2=Kelso, Paul |author3=James-Gregory, Sally |author4=Dodd, Vikram |date=17 June 2002|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=26 April 2012|location=London}}</ref> He was named one of the 20 most important Asians in British media in 2005.<ref name=\"AIM\">[http://www.asiansinmedia.org/top20/2005/1.php Most Powerful Asians in British Media: Lord Waheed Alli]. ''Asians in Media''</ref> At the same time, he maintains ties with his Caribbean roots, both with other British-Guyanese politicians such as [[Valerie Amos]] and [[Trevor Phillips]], and with President [[Bharrat Jagdeo]].<ref name=\"CV\">John Muir, [http://www.caribvoice.org/Profiles/peers.html \"Caribbean Peers\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927202004/http://www.caribvoice.org/Profiles/peers.html |date=27 September 2007 }}, Caribbean Voice, October 2001.</ref>\n\nHe is one of a group of highly successful Guyanese people in Britain ([[Michael White (journalist)|Michael White]] of ''[[The Guardian]]'' refers to them as the \"Guyanese mafia\"), which includes [[Raj Persaud]], [[Herman Ouseley]]<ref>Michael White, [https://www.theguardian.com/politics/blog/2009/aug/27/balls-gcse-results-michael-white \"Balls gets his retaliation in first as annual GCSE row begins\"], ''The Guardian'', 27 August 2009.</ref> and [[David Dabydeen]], [[Cynthia Pine]], [[Keith Waithe]] and [[Rudolph Dunbar]].<ref>''Guyanese Achievers UK'' (2007) by Dindayal Vidur.</ref>\n\nAlli grew up in humble surroundings, attended [[Harris Academy South Norwood|Stanley Technical College]] in [[South Norwood]] and left school at 16 with nine [[O-levels]].<ref name=\"KC\">[http://www.knittingcircle.org.uk/waheedalli.html Knitting Circle.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070307031738/http://www.knittingcircle.org.uk/waheedalli.html |date=7 March 2007 }}</ref>\n\n==Business career==\nAlli started work as a junior researcher for a finance magazine, crediting his first success to Salem Ghayar, who hired and mentored him.  After a few years of preparing monthly reports for potential investors, he was headhunted by Save & Prosper, part of [[Robert Fleming & Co.]].<ref name=\"asianoutlook.com\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20030308075823/http://www.asianoutlook.com/lordali.htm Interviewed by Shahid]. ''The Asian Outlook''. No date; approximately 2001.</ref> Eventually he returned to his original employer, and worked his way up in the media business within [[Robert Maxwell]]'s stable of publications.  He then went to [[City of London|the City]] for a second career in [[investment banking]], through which he became wealthy.<ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/1047062.stm|title=Profile: Lord Waheed Alli|date=29 November 2000|work=[[BBC News Online]]|accessdate=24 May 2009}}</ref> In the mid-1980s he met [[Charlie Parsons]], who was to become his business partner as well as his life partner.<ref name=\"The Independent (Saturday 06 June 2015)\">{{cite web|title=The Party Boys|publisher=The Independent. Saturday, 6 June 2015|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/the-party-boys-1196428.html|website=}}</ref>\n\nAlli's third career, and the first in which he achieved public prominence, was in the television industry.  He and Parsons set up [[24 Hour Productions]], which produced ''[[The Word (TV series)|The Word]]'', \"the most talked about television programme in Britain\".<ref name=\"KC\" /> In 1992 they merged with [[Bob Geldof]]'s [[Planet Pictures]] to form [[Planet 24]].  Such was its success that it became one of the largest TV production companies in the country, and the main independent supplier to [[Channel 4]].<ref name=\"KC\" /> It was responsible for genre-breaking programmes such as ''Big Breakfast'' and ''[[Survivor (TV series)|Survivor]]''. [[Carlton Television]] bought Planet 24 in March 1999 for \u00a315 million, with Alli and Parsons prudently retaining the rights to the lucrative ''Survivor'' format. Waheed Alli became a Carlton board director before stepping down a year later.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2002/jun/17/religion.immigrationpolicy|title=Profiles of 10 leading British Muslims|author1=Vasagar, Jeevan |author2=Kelso, Paul |author3=James-Gregory, Sally |author4=Dodd, Vikram |date=17 June 2002|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=24 May 2009|location=London}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2003 Alli took over as chairman of the [[intellectual property|media rights]] company [[Chorion (company)|Chorion Ltd]],<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/2871751/Hands-off-Noddy.html | location=London | work=The Daily Telegraph | title=Hands off Noddy! | date=14 December 2003}}</ref> which owns rights to [[Enid Blyton]] and [[Agatha Christie]], and has offices beyond the UK in New York, Sydney, and Tokyo.<ref name=\"AIM\" /> He was chairman of [[Alternative Investment Market|AIM]]-listed [[ASOS.com]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/business/8124164.stm|title=Overseas sales boost Asos profits|date=29 June 2009|work=[[bbc.co.uk]]|accessdate=29 June 2009}}</ref> and a director of [[Olga Television]], entertainer [[Paul O'Grady]]'s [[production company]]. He owns part of [[Shine Limited]], a media production company he co-founded in March 2001 with [[Elisabeth Murdoch (businesswoman)|Elisabeth Murdoch]], daughter of media-magnate [[Rupert Murdoch]]. In August 2011, he stepped down from the chairmanship of Chorion and sold half his stake in ASOS.com to start a new company called Silvergate Media.{{Citation needed|date=September 2012|reason=please provide source or remove}}\n\nHe was part of a failed \u00a3100m bid backed by [[private equity]] firm [[3i]] to buy [[Virgin Radio]] from [[SMG plc]] in 2005. In March 2007 he was appointed as SMG's non-executive director.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2007/mar/05/smg.citynews|title=SMG makes board appointments|last=Holmwood|first=Leigh|date=5 March 2007|work=[[guardian.co.uk]]|accessdate=24 May 2009|location=London}}</ref>\n\nAlli is a founder investor in Koovs, an Indian online retailer looking to replicate the success of Asos in the subcontinent. The company was set up in 2012 and intends to raise \u00a322m with a stock market listing on London's Aim.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/b8586954-4bb5-11e3-a02f-00144feabdc0.html#axzz2kVSow9B5|author=Duncan Robinson|work=Financial Times|date=12 November 2013|title=Ex-Asos boss to list Indian venture on Aim}}</ref>\nIn December 2019 the company goes into administration after funding isn't found.  The company is bought by SGIK 3 for 250,000. Shareholders lose millions.  SGIK 3 is Lord Ali's company, set up in the weeks prior to the collapse.<ref>https://www.morningstar.co.uk/uk/news/AN_1576002908644184200/update-koovs-sold-to-sgik-3-after-falling-in-administration.aspx</ref>\n==Politics==\nAlli joined the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] at the persuasion of his neighbour [[Emily Thornberry]], to whom he remains close.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2009/may/19/emily-thornberry-islington-mps-expenses |work=[[The Guardian]] |first=Aida |last=Edemariam |title=Right, so just what do you do all day? |date=19 May 2009 }}</ref> He is also close to [[Anji Hunter]], Director of Government Relations in [[Tony Blair]]'s first government.<ref>{{Cite news |first=Kamal |last=Ahmed |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2002/jun/02/tonyblair.schools |title=Inside Labour's young boy (and girl) network |work=[[The Observer]] |date=2 June 2002 }}</ref> [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|Prime Minister]] Blair used him for years as a means to help him reach out to a younger generation (aka \"[[Youth subculture|yoof culture]]\"),<ref name=\"BBC\" /> and as such he is considered{{by whom|date=July 2013}} one of \"[[Tony's Cronies]]\".<ref name=\"CV\" /> He was made a [[life peer]] as '''Baron Alli''', of [[Norbury]] in the [[London Borough of Croydon]], on 18 July 1998<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=55203 |date=22 July 1998 |page=7983}}</ref><ref>[https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/ld199798/minutes/980721/ldminute.htm Minutes and Order Paper \u2013 Minutes of Proceedings \u2013 The House of Lords] Parliament (19 July 1998). Retrieved on 15 March 2013.</ref> at the age of 34, becoming the youngest and the first openly gay peer in [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|Parliament]]. He sits on the Labour benches in the [[House of Lords]]. The [[BBC]] summarised his appointment as \"the antithesis of the stereotypical '[[The Establishment|establishment]]' peer \u2013 young, Asian and from the world of media and entertainment\".<ref name=\"BBC\"/>\n\nAlli has used his political position to argue for [[gay rights]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://kooth.com/|title=Kooth {{!}} Home|website=kooth.com|language=en|access-date=2018-04-23}}</ref> He spearheaded the campaign to repeal [[Section 28]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.gmax.co.za/think/history/2006/060316-clause28.html |title=What was Clause 28? |first=Liz |last=Highleyman |work=Gmax |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060814052339/http://www.gmax.co.za/think/history/2006/060316-clause28.html |date=16 February 2006 |archivedate=14 August 2006 |accessdate=24 June 2017 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> He advocated lowering the [[age of consent]] for homosexuals from 18 to 16, equal to heterosexuals; this eventually became law as the [[Sexual Offences (Amendment) Act 2000]]. It was during a heated exchange with conservative opponents, led by [[Janet Young, Baroness Young|Baroness Young]], that he informed his fellow peers that he was gay. In April 1999, he said in a speech, \"I have never been confused about my sexuality. I have been confused about the way I am treated as a result of it. The only confusion lies in the prejudice shown, some of it tonight [i.e. in the House], and much of it enshrined in the law.\"<ref name=\"BBC\"/><ref name=\"Hansard: Sexual Offences (Amendment) Act 2000\">{{cite Hansard |jurisdiction=United Kingdom |title=HL Deb 13 April 1999 vol 599 c737 |url=http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/lords/1999/apr/13/sexual-offences-amendment-bill#S5LV0599P0_19990413_HOL_256 |house=[[House of Lords]] |date=13 April 1999 |column=737 |speaker=Waheed Alli, Baron Alli |position=}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006, he participated the [[2006 World Outgames#International Conference on LGBT Human Rights|International Conference on LGBT Human Rights]] adopting [[Declaration of Montreal]] and in 2009, he spearheaded an effort to repeal clauses in the [[Civil Partnership Act 2004]] which prohibited religious institutions from conducting the ceremonies on their premises.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.churchofengland.org/our-views/home-and-community-affairs/home-affairs-policy/equality-bill/lord-alli's-amendment.aspx |title=Lord Alli's amendment |publisher=[[Church of England]] }}{{dead link |date=June 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/religion/7386492/Lord-Alli-attacks-bishops-in-gay-marriage-row.html |title=Lord Alli attacks bishops in 'gay marriage' row |last=Alderson |first=Andrew |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |quote=one of the few openly-gay Muslim politicians |accessdate=25 April 2012 |date=6 March 2010 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/8546827.stm |title=Church gay ceremonies ban lifted |work=[[BBC News Online]] |date=3 March 2010 }}</ref> This campaign culminated in a bipartisan amendment, which became part of the [[Equality Act 2010]].<ref>{{Cite news |first=Jerome |last=Taylor |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/gay-weddings-to-be-allowed-in-church-1915467.html |title=Gay weddings to be allowed in church |work=[[The Independent]] |date=3 March 2010 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-16203951 |title=Peer drops fight over same-sex ceremonies in churches |work=[[BBC News Online]] |date=15 December 2011 }}</ref> He influenced the draft Communications Bill in 2003.<ref name=\"AIM\" />\n\n==Other activities==\nAlli's work has been focused around gay rights, youth and education.  He is the former [[Chancellor (education)|Chancellor]] of [[De Montfort University]] in [[Leicester]]. He is also the President of the [[Croydon]] Youth Development Trust.<ref>[http://www.cydt.org.uk/index.html Croydon Youth Development Trust] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060620100247/http://www.cydt.org.uk/index.html |date=20 June 2006 }}</ref> He is a patron of Skillset,<ref>[http://www.skillset.org/skillset/governance/article_1844_1.asp Skillset Board of Patrons] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101129220527/http://skillset.org/skillset/governance/article_1844_1.asp |date=29 November 2010 }}</ref> the [[Sector Skills Council]] supporting skills and training within the creative media industries.\n\nIn Autumn 2008 he won a [[Stonewall Awards|Stonewall Award]] for the category of political figure. In 2002 he became a patron of [[The Albert Kennedy Trust]], stating: \"Being a teenager isn't easy and it's particularly difficult for vulnerable and [[social exclusion|socially excluded]] members of our community. The Albert Kennedy Trust offers young [[LGBT|gay men, lesbians and bisexuals]] a unique and targeted service. My first task as Patron will be to support plans to extend these services across the UK, to help the increasing number of young people contacting the Trust.\" He was a [[keynote speaker]] at the International Conference on [[LGBT social movements|LGBT Human Rights]], part of the [[2006 World Outgames]], which led to the [[Declaration of Montreal]]. Alli is a patron of Oxford Pride, the annual [[Pride parade|Pride event]] in Oxfordshire, and of [[Pride London]]. He is a patron of the [[Elton John AIDS Foundation]].<ref>[http://ejaf.com/about/our-patrons/ Elton John AIDS Foundation patrons]</ref>\n\nA portrait of Alli is in the [[National Portrait Gallery (United Kingdom)|National Portrait Gallery]] collection,<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20040926215213/http://www.npg.org.uk/live/search/person.asp?LinkID=mp66357 \"Waheed Alli, Baron Alli (1964-), Television producer and politician\"], National Portrait Gallery.</ref> which contains \"portraits of the Nation's great men and women\".<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.npg.org.uk/collections/about/primary-collection/learn-more-primary.php | title = National Portrait Gallery \u2013 Introduction to the Primary Collection | accessdate = 18 June 2013 | quote = \" The collections fulfil two enduring functions: to display portraits of the Nation's great men and women [and] to act as a national focus for the study and understanding of portraits and portraiture.\"}}</ref>\n\n==Arms==\n{{Infobox COA wide\n|image = [[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|centre|150px]][[File:Alli Escutcheon.png|centre|200px]]\n|escutcheon = Azure on a Cross Argent between four Suns issuing from the dexter and sinister chief and from the dexter and sinister base a Cross flory Gules each limb banded Or\n|crest = A Scarlet Ibis proper grasping in the sinister claws a Rose Gules barbed seeded slipped and leaved Or\n|supporters = On either side a Jaguar Or spotted Azure grasping in the interior forefoot a Sugar Cain Or\n|motto = Pro multis non pro paucis <ref>http://www.cracroftspeerage.co.uk/online/content/lp1958%20a.htm</ref>\n|badge = Out of a Rim Or fimbriated Argent the Jaguar Heads conjoined Or spotted Azure }}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|United Kingdom|Biography|Politics|LGBT}}\n*{{UK Peer links |parliament = waheed-alli/26958 |hansard = mr-waheed-alli |hansardcurr= 3639 |guardian= |publicwhip = Lord_Alli |theywork= lord_alli | record = Waheed-Alli/1834 | bbc = 26958.stm | journalisted = waheed-alli }}\n*[https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/ld199798/minutes/980721/ldminute.htm Announcement of his introduction at the House of Lords], House of Lords minutes of proceedings, 21 July 1998\n*[http://oxfordpride.org.uk Oxford Pride]\n*[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/1047062.stm  BBC profile], 29 November 2000.\n*[http://www.asiansinmedia.org/top20/2005/1.php Asians in Media profile], 2005.\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070927202004/http://www.caribvoice.org/Profiles/peers.html Caribbean Voice profile], October 2001.\n*[http://www.knittingcircle.org.uk/waheedalli Knitting Circle profile]{{dead link|date=May 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, with press cuttings\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070403225421/http://www.akt.org.uk/patrons.htm The Albert Kennedy Trust]\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-aca}}\n{{Succession box\n  | title  = [[De Montfort University|Chancellor of De Montfort University]]\n  | years  = 2006\u20132015\n  | before = [[Usha Prashar, Baroness Prashar|Baroness Usha Prashar]]\n  | after = [[Doreen Lawrence|Baroness Doreen Lawrence]]\n}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Alli, Waheed Alli, Baron}}\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:British politicians of Indian descent]]\n[[Category:Gay politicians]]\n[[Category:LGBT Muslims]]\n[[Category:English businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) life peers]]\n[[Category:English people of Indo-Guyanese descent]]\n[[Category:English people of Indo-Trinidadian descent]]\n[[Category:English Muslims]]\n[[Category:People associated with De Montfort University]]\n[[Category:LGBT businesspeople from the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:LGBT politicians from England]]\n[[Category:LGBT life peers]]\n[[Category:Gay peers]]\n", "name_user": "Jambonkoovs", "label": "safe", "comment": "Just to say waheed is famous", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Waheed_Alli,_Baron_Alli"}
{"title_page": "Big George Brock", "text_new": "{{short description|American blues musician|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| background       = solo_singer\n| name             = Big George Brock\n| birth_name       = George Brock\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date|1932|5|16}}\n| death_date       = {{Death date and age|2020|4|10|1932|5|16}}\n| occupation       = Musician\n| instrument       = Harmonica\n| birth_place      = [[Grenada, Mississippi]], U.S.\n| associated_acts  = [[Muddy Waters]]<br/>[[Howlin' Wolf]]<br/>[[Albert King]]\n}}\n\n'''George Brock''' (May 16, 1932 &ndash; April 10, 2020), billed as '''Big George Brock''', was an American blues musician. A native of Mississippi, he moved to Missouri in the 1950s and operated a series of nightclubs. He played alongside [[Muddy Waters]], [[Howlin' Wolf]], [[Jimmy Reed]], and [[Albert King]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stlmag.com/St-Louis-Magazine/April-2012/The-Best-St-Louis-Blues-Musicians-of-All-Time/|title=The Best St. Louis Blues Musicians of All Time|last=|first=|date=June 1, 2012|website=St. Louis Post-Dispatch|language=en-us|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=}}</ref> Brock starred in the 2006 film ''Hard Times'', a documentary about his life.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.stlmag.com/api/content/00b3947a-ef7a-11e5-ab4c-22000b078648/|title=Hard Times: Talking to Big George Brock|last=Cooperman|first=Jeannette|date=March 21, 2016|website=St. Louis Post-Dispatch|language=en-us|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Life and career ==\nBrock was born in [[Grenada, Mississippi]] on May 16, 1932.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nationalbluesmuseum.org/news/national-blues-museum-host-concert-honor-big-george-brock-saturday-april-1-2017/|title=The National Blues Museum to Host Concert in Honor of Big George Brock on Saturday, April 1, 2017|last=|first=|date=March 21, 2017|website=National Blues Museum|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=}}</ref> By the time he was eight, he was working as a [[Sharecropping|sharecropper]] picking cotton.<ref name=\":0\" /> Brock was surrounded by blues music, he recalled that Brock says, \"the blues grew like grass out of the ground.\" His father taught hims and his brothers how to play harmonica as a child.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TtOJCgAAQBAJ&pg=PT5&dq=Big+George+Brock+club+caravan&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjyi9vXh_3mAhWDmeAKHVtdDtcQ6AEwAXoECAYQAg#v=onepage&q=Big%20George%20Brock&f=false|title=Hidden History of Mississippi Blues|last=Stolle|first=Roger|date=2011-04-01|publisher=Arcadia Publishing|isbn=978-1-61423-013-7|language=en}}</ref>\n\nAs a teenager he moved to [[Mattson, Mississippi]]. There he met [[Muddy Waters]], and they performed together on weekends.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=http://mississippibluesproject.org/2012/07/12/artist-profile-big-george-brock/|title=Artist Profile: Big George Brock|last=|first=|date=July 12, 2012|website=Mississippi Blues Project|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=}}</ref> In the late 1940s he moved to [[Walls, Mississippi]]. While working as a pipeliner on [[U.S. Route 61|Highway 61]], Brock met [[Howlin' Wolf]]. He became his roadie and performed with him.<ref name=\":2\" /> Brock asldo met [[Memphis Minnie]] in Walls and jamed with him at house parties.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nBrock moved to [[St. Louis]] in 1950 where he was an amateur [[Boxing|boxer]] for a while.<ref name=\":0\" /> In 1952, boxer [[Sonny Liston]] was training at a gym alongside Brock. Liston challenged Brock to [[sparring]] match. Brock won the fight in the second round, recalling that \"he'd just come out of the pen. He thought he was pretty tough.\"<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.stltoday.com/entertainment/music/blues-profile-big-george-brock/article_b17d08a8-6fed-11df-a0dc-00127992bc8b.html|title=BLUES PROFILE: Big George Brock|last=Moore|first=Doug|date=June 4, 2007|website=St. Louis Post-Dispatch|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Brock decided to focus on his music career because it was more lucrative, forming his own band Big George & the Houserockers.<ref name=\":2\" /> Blues guitarist [[Albert King]] played in Brock's band before forming his own.<ref name=\":4\" /> \n\nIn 1952, Brock opened his own nightclub, Club Caravan, near North Garrison and Franklin avenues. Brock worked as a [[Bouncer (doorman)|bouncer]] and performed there with is band which at times featured King, Big Baddy Smitty, or Riley Coatie on lead guitar.<ref name=\":2\" /> The club hosted acts such as Howlin' Wolf, Muddy Waters, [[Ike & Tina Turner]], and [[Jimmy Reed]].<ref name=\":4\" /> \n\nIn the early 1960s, Muddy Waters arranged for him to meet with the executives of [[Chess Records]]. Brock turned the record deal because although he was  offered a tour bus and proceeds from the shows, he wouldn't have received any royalties from his recordings.<ref name=\":4\" /> He decided to continue playing the club circuit, at one point he owned as many as three nightclubs at once. Brock closed the Club Caravan after his wife was killed during shooting incident in 1970. He opened another Club Caravan at Delmar Boulevard and Taylor Avenue, but that closed in the late 1980s.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nIn 2005, Brock signed to the label Cat Head Delta Blues & Folk Art. He put out the album ''Club Caravan'' which received favorable reviews and a [[Blues Music Award]] nomination last year for best comeback album. In 2006 he released the album ''Round Two'', which received three Blues Music Award nominations.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nIn 2006, Brock was featured in a documentary about his life titled ''Hard Times''. In the film he visits the plantations where he worked as a child in Mississippi.<ref name=\":3\" /> \n\nIn 2017, Brock was honored with a special concert at the [[National Blues Museum]] in St. Louis.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stltoday.com/entertainment/music/kevin-johnson/king-of-st-louis-blues-big-george-brock-to-be/article_81680d62-b4a7-5440-a7b3-ae8fabfd281b.html|title='King of St. Louis Blues' Big George Brock to be honored at National Blues Museum|last=Johnson|first=Kevin C.|date=March 16, 2017|website=St. Louis Post-Dispatch|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=}}</ref> Brock toured overseas in England, Italy, Switzerland and France.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.deltabluesmuseum.org/events-blues-bus.aspx|title=BIG BROCK'S 'BLUES BUS' HITS HIGHWAY TO MISSISSIPPI DELTA|last=|first=|date=July 29, 2009|website=Delta Blues Museum|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=}}</ref> He continued to perform and regularly headlined various blues festivals, including the Bluesweek Festival and the Big Muddy Blues Festival.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stltoday.com/entertainment/music/kevin-johnson/big-muddy-blues-festival-returning-as-a-one-day-free/article_f22212be-0946-5a34-b1e8-5cdb7f6e908d.html|title=Big Muddy Blues Festival returning as a one-day free event|last=Johnson|first=Kevin C.|date=August 9, 2019|website=St. Louis Post-Dispatch|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stltoday.com/entertainment/music/kevin-johnson/mavis-staples-headlining-bluesweek-downtown/article_3fb6a1dc-8c8b-5a1b-bb3e-dd39400a64d2.html|title=Mavis Staples headlining Bluesweek 2013 downtown|last=Johnson|first=Kevin C.|date=March 7, 2013|website=St. Louis Post-Dispatch|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nBrock was married three times and claimed to have forty-two children.<ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":2\" />\n\nBrock died on April 10, 2020 at the age of 87.<ref name=\"STL 10Apr20\">{{cite news |last=Johnson |first=Kevin C. |url=https://www.stltoday.com/entertainment/music/kevin-johnson/st-louis-blues-legend-big-george-brock-has-died-family-confirms/article_caa23dc4-88ee-5741-be6d-2d40c0cb0d79.html |title=St. Louis blues legend Big George Brock has died, family confirms |work=St. Louis Post-Dispatch |date=April 10, 2020 |accessdate=April 10, 2020 }}</ref>\n\n== Discography ==\n\n=== Albums ===\n\n* ''I Got To Keep My Bedroom Door Locked''\n* ''Should Have Been There''\n* 1999: ''Front Door Man'' (Tee-Ti)\n* 2005: Big George Brock & The Houserockers \u2013 ''Club Caravan'' (Cat Head Delta Blues & Folk Art, Inc.)\n* 2006: ''Round Two'' (Cat Head Delta Blues & Folk Art, Inc.)\n* 2007: ''Live At Seventy Five'' (Cat Head Delta Blues & Folk Art, Inc.)\n* 2007: ''Heavyweight Blues'' (APO Records)\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n== External links ==\n\n* [https://www.imdb.com/name/nm4776730/?ref_=tt_ov_st_sm Big George Brock] on [[IMDb]]\n* [http://mississippibluesproject.org/2012/07/12/artist-profile-big-george-brock/ Big George Brock] on Mississippi Blues Project\n* [https://www.allmusic.com/artist/big-george-brock-mn0000636700/discography Big George Brock discography] on [[AllMusic]]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brock, Big George}}\n[[Category:1932 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:American blues harmonica players]]\n[[Category:American rhythm and blues singers]]\n[[Category:American blues singers]]\n[[Category:Music of St. Louis]]\n[[Category:St. Louis blues musicians]]\n[[Category:Blues musicians from Mississippi]]\n[[Category:People from Grenada, Mississippi]]\n[[Category:People from Coahoma County, Mississippi]]\n[[Category:People from Walls, Mississippi]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American blues musician|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| background       = solo_singer\n| name             = Big George Brock\n| birth_name       = George Brock\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date|1932|5|16}}\n| death_date  =  {{Death date and age|2020|4|10|1932|5|16}}\n| occupation       = Musician\n| instrument       = Harmonica\n| birth_place      = [[Grenada, Mississippi]], U.S.\n| associated_acts  = [[Muddy Waters]]<br/>[[Howlin' Wolf]]<br/>[[Albert King]]\n}}\n\n'''George Brock''' (May 16, 1932 &ndash; April 10, 2020), billed as '''Big George Brock''', was an American blues musician. A native of Mississippi, he moved to Missouri in the 1950s and operated a series of nightclubs. He played alongside [[Muddy Waters]], [[Howlin' Wolf]], [[Jimmy Reed]], and [[Albert King]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stlmag.com/St-Louis-Magazine/April-2012/The-Best-St-Louis-Blues-Musicians-of-All-Time/|title=The Best St. Louis Blues Musicians of All Time|last=|first=|date=June 1, 2012|website=St. Louis Post-Dispatch|language=en-us|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=}}</ref> Brock starred in the 2006 film ''Hard Times'', a documentary about his life.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.stlmag.com/api/content/00b3947a-ef7a-11e5-ab4c-22000b078648/|title=Hard Times: Talking to Big George Brock|last=Cooperman|first=Jeannette|date=March 21, 2016|website=St. Louis Post-Dispatch|language=en-us|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Life and career ==\nBrock was born in [[Grenada, Mississippi]] on May 16, 1932.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nationalbluesmuseum.org/news/national-blues-museum-host-concert-honor-big-george-brock-saturday-april-1-2017/|title=The National Blues Museum to Host Concert in Honor of Big George Brock on Saturday, April 1, 2017|last=|first=|date=March 21, 2017|website=National Blues Museum|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=}}</ref> By the time he was eight, he was working as a [[Sharecropping|sharecropper]] picking cotton.<ref name=\":0\" /> Brock was surrounded by blues music, he recalled that Brock says, \"the blues grew like grass out of the ground.\" His father taught hims and his brothers how to play harmonica as a child.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TtOJCgAAQBAJ&pg=PT5&dq=Big+George+Brock+club+caravan&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjyi9vXh_3mAhWDmeAKHVtdDtcQ6AEwAXoECAYQAg#v=onepage&q=Big%20George%20Brock&f=false|title=Hidden History of Mississippi Blues|last=Stolle|first=Roger|date=2011-04-01|publisher=Arcadia Publishing|isbn=978-1-61423-013-7|language=en}}</ref>\n\nAs a teenager he moved to [[Mattson, Mississippi]]. There he met [[Muddy Waters]], and they performed together on weekends.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=http://mississippibluesproject.org/2012/07/12/artist-profile-big-george-brock/|title=Artist Profile: Big George Brock|last=|first=|date=July 12, 2012|website=Mississippi Blues Project|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=}}</ref> In the late 1940s he moved to [[Walls, Mississippi]]. While working as a pipeliner on [[U.S. Route 61|Highway 61]], Brock met [[Howlin' Wolf]]. He became his roadie and performed with him.<ref name=\":2\" /> Brock asldo met [[Memphis Minnie]] in Walls and jamed with him at house parties.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nBrock moved to [[St. Louis]] in 1950 where he was an amateur [[Boxing|boxer]] for a while.<ref name=\":0\" /> In 1952, boxer [[Sonny Liston]] was training at a gym alongside Brock. Liston challenged Brock to [[sparring]] match. Brock won the fight in the second round, recalling that \"he'd just come out of the pen. He thought he was pretty tough.\"<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.stltoday.com/entertainment/music/blues-profile-big-george-brock/article_b17d08a8-6fed-11df-a0dc-00127992bc8b.html|title=BLUES PROFILE: Big George Brock|last=Moore|first=Doug|date=June 4, 2007|website=St. Louis Post-Dispatch|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Brock decided to focus on his music career because it was more lucrative, forming his own band Big George & the Houserockers.<ref name=\":2\" /> Blues guitarist [[Albert King]] played in Brock's band before forming his own.<ref name=\":4\" /> \n\nIn 1952, Brock opened his own nightclub, Club Caravan, near North Garrison and Franklin avenues. Brock worked as a [[Bouncer (doorman)|bouncer]] and performed there with is band which at times featured King, Big Baddy Smitty, or Riley Coatie on lead guitar.<ref name=\":2\" /> The club hosted acts such as Howlin' Wolf, Muddy Waters, [[Ike & Tina Turner]], and [[Jimmy Reed]].<ref name=\":4\" /> \n\nIn the early 1960s, Muddy Waters arranged for him to meet with the executives of [[Chess Records]]. Brock turned the record deal because although he was  offered a tour bus and proceeds from the shows, he wouldn't have received any royalties from his recordings.<ref name=\":4\" /> He decided to continue playing the club circuit, at one point he owned as many as three nightclubs at once. Brock closed the Club Caravan after his wife was killed during shooting incident in 1970. He opened another Club Caravan at Delmar Boulevard and Taylor Avenue, but that closed in the late 1980s.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nIn 2005, Brock signed to the label Cat Head Delta Blues & Folk Art. He put out the album ''Club Caravan'' which received favorable reviews and a [[Blues Music Award]] nomination last year for best comeback album. In 2006 he released the album ''Round Two'', which received three Blues Music Award nominations.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nIn 2006, Brock was featured in a documentary about his life titled ''Hard Times''. In the film he visits the plantations where he worked as a child in Mississippi.<ref name=\":3\" /> \n\nIn 2017, Brock was honored with a special concert at the [[National Blues Museum]] in St. Louis.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stltoday.com/entertainment/music/kevin-johnson/king-of-st-louis-blues-big-george-brock-to-be/article_81680d62-b4a7-5440-a7b3-ae8fabfd281b.html|title='King of St. Louis Blues' Big George Brock to be honored at National Blues Museum|last=Johnson|first=Kevin C.|date=March 16, 2017|website=St. Louis Post-Dispatch|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=}}</ref> Brock toured overseas in England, Italy, Switzerland and France.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.deltabluesmuseum.org/events-blues-bus.aspx|title=BIG BROCK'S 'BLUES BUS' HITS HIGHWAY TO MISSISSIPPI DELTA|last=|first=|date=July 29, 2009|website=Delta Blues Museum|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=}}</ref> He continued to perform and regularly headlined various blues festivals, including the Bluesweek Festival and the Big Muddy Blues Festival.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stltoday.com/entertainment/music/kevin-johnson/big-muddy-blues-festival-returning-as-a-one-day-free/article_f22212be-0946-5a34-b1e8-5cdb7f6e908d.html|title=Big Muddy Blues Festival returning as a one-day free event|last=Johnson|first=Kevin C.|date=August 9, 2019|website=St. Louis Post-Dispatch|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stltoday.com/entertainment/music/kevin-johnson/mavis-staples-headlining-bluesweek-downtown/article_3fb6a1dc-8c8b-5a1b-bb3e-dd39400a64d2.html|title=Mavis Staples headlining Bluesweek 2013 downtown|last=Johnson|first=Kevin C.|date=March 7, 2013|website=St. Louis Post-Dispatch|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nBrock was married three times and claimed to have forty-two children.<ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":2\" />\n\nBrock died on April 10, 2020 at the age of 87.<ref>https://www.stltoday.com/entertainment/music/kevin-johnson/st-louis-blues-legend-big-george-brock-has-died-family-confirms/article_caa23dc4-88ee-5741-be6d-2d40c0cb0d79.html</ref>\n\n== Discography ==\n\n=== Albums ===\n\n* ''I Got To Keep My Bedroom Door Locked''\n* ''Should Have Been There''\n* 1999: ''Front Door Man'' (Tee-Ti)\n* 2005: Big George Brock & The Houserockers \u2013 ''Club Caravan'' (Cat Head Delta Blues & Folk Art, Inc.)\n* 2006: ''Round Two'' (Cat Head Delta Blues & Folk Art, Inc.)\n* 2007: ''Live At Seventy Five'' (Cat Head Delta Blues & Folk Art, Inc.)\n* 2007: ''Heavyweight Blues'' (APO Records)\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n== External links ==\n\n* [https://www.imdb.com/name/nm4776730/?ref_=tt_ov_st_sm Big George Brock] on [[IMDb]]\n* [http://mississippibluesproject.org/2012/07/12/artist-profile-big-george-brock/ Big George Brock] on Mississippi Blues Project\n*[https://www.allmusic.com/artist/big-george-brock-mn0000636700/discography Big George Brock discography] on [[AllMusic]]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brock, Big George}}\n[[Category:1932 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:American blues harmonica players]]\n[[Category:American rhythm and blues singers]]\n[[Category:American blues singers]]\n[[Category:Music of St. Louis]]\n[[Category:St. Louis blues musicians]]\n[[Category:Blues musicians from Mississippi]]\n[[Category:People from Grenada, Mississippi]]\n[[Category:People from Coahoma County, Mississippi]]\n[[Category:People from Walls, Mississippi]]\n", "name_user": "Nick", "label": "safe", "comment": "update reference", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_George_Brock"}
{"title_page": "CR-4056", "text_new": "{{drugbox\n| IUPAC_name        = 6-(1H-imidazol-1-yl)-2-phenylquinazoline\n| image             = CR-4056_structure.png\n| CAS_number_Ref = {{cascite|correct|CAS}}\n| CAS_number        = 1004997-71-0 \n| ATC_prefix        =\n| ATC_suffix        =\n| PubChem           = 24898732\n| UNII_Ref = {{fdacite|correct|FDA}}\n| UNII              = W9SQ1X2NPZ\n| DrugBank          =\n| ChemSpiderID = \n| C=17|H=12|N=4\n| molecular_weight  = 272.304 g/mol\n| smiles            = C1(C2=CC=CC=C2)=NC=C3C=C(N4C=CN=C4)C=CC3=N1\n| StdInChI = 1S/C17H12N4/c1-2-4-13(5-3-1)17-19-11-14-10-15(6-7-16(14)20-17)21-9-8-18-12-21/h1-12H \n| StdInChIKey = CSZGXYBGYFNSCO-UHFFFAOYSA-N\n| bioavailability   =\n| protein_bound     =\n| metabolism        =\n| elimination_half-life =\n| excretion         =\n| pregnancy_AU      =  <!-- A / B1 / B2 / B3 / C / D / X -->\n| pregnancy_US      =  <!-- A / B            / C / D / X -->\n| pregnancy_category=\n| legal_AU          =  <!-- Unscheduled / S2 / S3 / S4 / S5 / S6 / S7 / S8 / S9 -->\n| legal_CA          =  \n| legal_UK          =  \n| legal_US          =  <!-- OTC                   / Rx-only  / Schedule I, II, III, IV, V -->\n| legal_status      =\n| routes_of_administration =\n}}\n\n'''CR-4056''' is an [[analgesic]] drug candidate with a novel mechanism of action, acting as a [[Ligand (biochemistry)|ligand]] for the [[imidazoline receptor]] I<sub>2</sub>. It showed promising results in animal studies against various types of [[neuropathic pain]], and has reached Phase II human [[clinical trial]]s as a potential treatment for pain associated with [[osteoarthritis]].<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Ferrari F, Fiorentino S, Mennuni L, Garofalo P, Letari O, Mandelli S, Giordani A, Lanza M, Caselli G | title = Analgesic efficacy of CR4056, a novel imidazoline-2 receptor ligand, in rat models of inflammatory and neuropathic pain | journal = Journal of Pain Research | volume = 4 | pages = 111\u201325 | date = 2011 | pmid =